The area of $\triangle ADG$ is $4 + 3\sqrt{2}$.

The key insight is to recognize that $9$ can be written as $3^2$. This allows us to simplify the expression by using the properties of exponents, specifically $(a^m)^n = a^{mn}$ and $\sqrt{a^n} = a^{n/2}$ for even $n$.
Step 1: Rewrite $9$ as $3^2$.
$$\begin{align*}
\sqrt{9^3} &= \sqrt{(3^2)^3}
\end{align*}$$

Step 2: Use the property $(a^m)^n = a^{mn}$ to simplify the exponent.
$$\begin{align*}
\sqrt{(3^2)^3} &= \sqrt{3^{2 \cdot 3}} \\
&= \sqrt{3^6}
\end{align*}$$

Step 3: Use the property $\sqrt{a^n} = a^{n/2}$ for even $n$ to simplify the square root.
$$\begin{align*}
\sqrt{3^6} &= 3^{6/2} \\
&= 3^3
\end{align*}$$

Step 4: Evaluate $3^3$.
$$\begin{align*}
3^3 &= 27
\end{align*}$$
Therefore, $\sqrt{9^3} = \boxed{27}$.

The key insight in this problem is to recognize the common factor of 10 among the terms inside the cube root. By factoring out this common factor, we can simplify the expression and evaluate the cube root more easily. This approach takes advantage of the properties of exponents and the ability to factor out common terms from a sum.
Step 1: Notice that all three integers inside the cube root have a common factor of 10. We can factor this out:
$$\begin{align*}
\sqrt[3]{30^3+40^3+50^3} &= \sqrt[3]{(10 \cdot 3)^3 + (10 \cdot 4)^3 + (10 \cdot 5)^3} \\
&= \sqrt[3]{10^3 \cdot 3^3 + 10^3 \cdot 4^3 + 10^3 \cdot 5^3}
\end{align*}$$

Step 2: Using the property $(ab)^n = a^n b^n$, we can simplify further:
$$\begin{align*}
\sqrt[3]{10^3 \cdot 3^3 + 10^3 \cdot 4^3 + 10^3 \cdot 5^3} &= \sqrt[3]{10^3(3^3 + 4^3 + 5^3)} \\
&= 10 \sqrt[3]{3^3 + 4^3 + 5^3}
\end{align*}$$

Step 3: Evaluate the expression under the cube root:
$$\begin{align*}
10 \sqrt[3]{3^3 + 4^3 + 5^3} &= 10 \sqrt[3]{27 + 64 + 125} \\
&= 10 \sqrt[3]{216}
\end{align*}$$

Step 4: Simplify the cube root:
$$\begin{align*}
10 \sqrt[3]{216} &= 10 \sqrt[3]{6^3} \\
&= 10 \cdot 6 \\
&= 60
\end{align*}$$

The key insight is to recognize that since the repetend has 18 digits, the 39th digit will be the same as the $(39 \bmod 18)$th digit, which is the 3rd digit after the decimal point. We can find this digit by directly dividing 1 by 19.
1) Recognize that the repetend has 18 digits.
2) Observe that $39 = 2 \times 18 + 3$, so the 39th digit is the same as the 3rd digit after the decimal point.
3) Divide 1 by 19 to find the 3rd digit after the decimal point:

$$
